title: Part 5
content:
Part 5

AROUND 8:00 P.M., the Class C students started trickling into their tents.

It was still the first day of the exam and aside from the surprise attacks, not a single engagement with another class had occurred.

As tomorrow and the day after arrived, the scent of battle would inevitably draw closer.

Avoiding needless exertion and striving to recover our stamina was the best move we could make right now.

Five of the boys had gathered in the large tent I was using, but surprisingly, they were lively and engaged in idle chatter, showing no signs of negativity.

A major factor contributing to this positivity was undoubtedly Hashimoto's presence.

He constantly brought up new topics to keep us from falling into the mindset that we might lose.

My classmates weren't fools. If they dwelled on their current predicament, things would inevitably become gloomy. That was why they were quick to join in, allowing themselves to be influenced by Hashimoto's demeanor.

The idle chatter shifted away from class matters and moved on to funny stories from the past.

Once Satonaka finished his story, all eyes turned to Hashimoto, who was sitting beside him.

"Well then, guess I'll tell a story I just remembered."

Without refusing, he cheerfully began to speak.

Seeing that made me realize once again that being a cheerful character is a talent in itself.

"Back in my third year of middle school, I met up with a classmate from elementary school and we biked to this ramen and udon place. It was a big place and there were a bunch of bikes in the bike rack. But then, there was this one bike parked outside the rack, in a car's parking spot. We didn't think anything of it and parked our bikes on either side of it. Just as we were about to go in, the guy who owned the bike in the parking spot—some gloomy-looking college-aged dude—came out."

Hashimoto continued, laughing amusedly as he recalled the memory.

"As we passed each other, he was looking at our bikes and muttering complaints. So, I asked him what was up and he goes, 'I can't get my bike out because yours are in the way.' But like, there was plenty of space between our bikes, you know? Anyway, I figured I'd just move it for him, but as I started to, he said, 'Don't park here, it's a nuisance.' That kinda pissed me off, so I shot back, 'You're the one parked in a car's spot.' Then he starts yelling back at me all fast, spouting some lame excuse like, 'Well, you guys parked two bikes'—"

"Dude, if you parked your bike in a car spot too, then you're also in the wrong."

A punch of pure logic flew from Matoba.

"Yeah, well. I know that, but it was just funny seeing him get pissed at us younger guys like he wasn't at fault at all. If it'd been some scary dude parked there, he definitely wouldn't have said a word. The moment we glared at him, he just muttered something under his breath and took off."

Regardless of whether Hashimoto was in the right or not, I figured everyone probably had one or two funny stories from before high school.

"You tell us something too, Ayanokouji. It can be a stupid story like mine."

I had a feeling my turn would be coming up soon.

However, I didn't have a single funny story to share.

"Sorry, but I have to step out. An issue came up that I need to deal with for tomorrow."

I sat up and gave my excuse.

"Oh, is that so? Can't be helped then."

If it was a problem related to the special exam, no one, including Hashimoto, would object.

Hashimoto seemed to have started another funny story from his stockpile, so I left the tent, relieved.

It might have seemed like I was running away, but I hoped they'd forgive me since it was true that I had a problem to deal with before the special exam resumed tomorrow.

It was past 9:00 p.m. and as far as I could see, everyone was inside their tents. Few seemed to be asleep, however, as the sound of chatter was constant. A short distance away in the darkness, lanterns glowed faintly in several of the tents standing side-by-side. The entrances were open, but a mesh screen kept insects out. It was as if the students, protected by their small sanctuaries, were trying to escape their anxiety and enjoy their current circumstances in a positive way, all while maintaining their distance.

"It seems they still have some mental fortitude left."

Or perhaps it was because they felt such hardship that they huddled together for protection.

Either way, that wouldn't be a problem until the exam started tomorrow.

The tent used by the person I was looking for was a two-person model and its flap was closed.

"I have a small favor to ask of you, Shiraishi. Do you have a moment?"

I didn't think she would be asleep yet, but I called out to her tentatively.

Then, I heard the faint rustle of fabric from inside the tent and the closed entrance soon opened. She held a lantern in her hand and its light softly spread to the surroundings.

"Good evening, Ayanokouji-kun. Is something the matter?"

Shiraishi, who was using a two-person tent, handed the lantern to me for a moment and then quietly crawled out.

"I'd like to talk for a bit. Can you spare the time?"

"To talk...?"

Shiraishi showed a rare moment of bewilderment. From behind her, another person, her tent-mate Hoashi, peeked out, unable to hide her grin.

"Hey, hey. You should probably make sure the other boys don't see you, you know? It'll be a huge mess if they do."

"It's not like that. Right, Ayanokouji-kun?"

"Yeah—it's not like that."

What did she mean by 'that'?

For a moment, I considered it, but the faces of Yoshida and Shimazaki immediately came to mind.

The act of calling Shiraishi out of her tent in the middle of the night would certainly appear suspicious if anyone saw.

"You can relax. It's about the exam from tomorrow onwards."

I explained as much to Hoashi just in case, but her eyes were smiling and it was doubtful whether she believed me.

As Hoashi saw us off, I moved a short distance away from the campsite with Shiraishi, who held a lantern in one hand.

"Is this a private matter?"

"Something like that."

Shiraishi's expression, illuminated by the dim light, had already returned to its usual—to borrow Yoshida's words—mysterious atmosphere.

"So, what was it you wanted to discuss with me?"

"If there was anything about my command and actions today that made you feel uneasy, I want you to tell me. I'm starting to have doubts about how to proceed from here."

"Unease and doubts?"

Although she immediately understood why she'd been summoned, Shiraishi brought her free hand to her mouth, looking puzzled.

"It's quite unexpected for you to harbor such unease and doubts, Ayanokouji-kun. I thought you were the type of person who considers everything and arrives at the answers all on your own and without any hesitation."

'Unexpected.' That one word from Shiraishi, casually included in her sentence.

I felt a new sense of unease.

The feeling I got from Shiraishi right after the surprise attack began to magnify.

The outcome of the attack that made even Hashimoto concerned.

In contrast, Shiraishi showed no doubt whatsoever that we might lose.

But for now, I decided to continue our conversation.

"I apologize if I seemed like an unreliable leader."

"That's not true at all. At the very least, I trust you. I believe that in the end, you will most certainly meet my expectations. Therefore, there's not a single thing I'm uneasy about."

Staring straight at me, Shiraishi answered without a hint of hesitation.

"If you were hoping for a reprimand, does this mean I failed to meet your expectations?"

"If you don't doubt my ability, even though I couldn't predict the surprise attack, then that's fine. I understand now that you trust me, Shiraishi."

Nodding yes, Shiraishi gave me an even wider smile.

"Then I'll make use of that trust without reservation."

"I'm prepared to help with anything, as long as it's within my power."

I finished my conversation with Shiraishi and walked her to her tent.

Hoashi's surprised greeting of, "You're back already?" was rather memorable.

On my way back alone to the tent where Hashimoto and the others waited, I glanced back at Shiraishi and Hoashi's tent.

Shiraishi, who'd nodded without hesitation that she trusted me.

A divergence from the impression I'd had of the student named Shiraishi Asuka.

She was able to show respect for others. If she thought it was for their own good, she would tell a gentle lie without hesitation.

Conversely, if she thought it wouldn't be for their own good, she would speak her true feelings.

She hadn't even tried to blame me for my mistake and said that she trusted me from the bottom of her heart.

The damage from the surprise attack was considerable; it wasn't something that could be overlooked as a simple mistake.

Shiraishi, with whom I'd first spoken to alone in an empty classroom early in the morning on the second day of Class C.

That scene had certainly been a gift of chance, but I questioned whether the same was true for our other encounters.

It was still June; I'd only spent about two months with the students of Class C.

True, it wasn't as if we'd had no contact at all during our first and second years, but I had only very recently begun to take the lead.

Even the boys, Yoshida and Shimazaki, didn't understand me well yet and it was likely the same for Hashimoto, who acted as my aide.

It was an incident that would cause anyone—Hashimoto, Matoba, Hoashi, Morishita—to feel a touch of unease.

Since they didn't know me well, it was normal for them to have doubts.

Yes, that was the part that was abnormal.

Why had she found it surprising that I, as the leader, would feel anxiety and uncertainty?

She wasn't a student incapable of thought.

A statement she couldn't have made unless she'd known me from before we became third-years.

"A connection to Sakayanagi... or perhaps, a similar—student, is it?"

Either way, it was a trivial matter.

Still, I made a point not to forget to keep it in my memory.
